You aren&#39;t creating a new array type, you&#39;re creating a class which holds an array. Thus `PrimitiveArray intArray[]`, aka a `PrimitiveArray[]`, isn&#39;t quite what you want. It&#39;d just be a plain `PrimitiveArray`, which already denotes something holding an array field.

    public class PrimitiveArray {
        int[] internal; //this data should be accessed through a method, encapsulation
    
        public PrimitiveArray(int amount) {
            this.internal = new int[amount];
        }
    }

    public class Main {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Random rand = new Random();
    
            PrimitiveArray intArray = new PrimitiveArray(5);
            //this may do well in the constructor, which you can pass your random to
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; intArray.internal.length; i++){
                intArray.internal[i] = rand.nextInt();
            }
        }
    }

Let&#39;s start with `PrimitiveArray`, there is an `intArray` field which is visible to members of the same package (which is a little odd); normally you&#39;d make that `private`. You haven&#39;t given `PrimitiveArray` a `length` field. And you need methods for accessing and changing the values within your `intArray`. Then, I believe you might find overriding `toString()` is an easy way to output the values. Something like,

	public class PrimitiveArray {
		private int[] intArray;
		public int length;

		public PrimitiveArray(int amount) {
			this.length = amount;
			this.intArray = new int[amount];
		}

		public void set(int i, int v) {
			if (i &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; i &lt; length) {
				this.intArray[i] = v;
			}
		}

		public int get(int i) {
			if (i &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; i &lt; length) {
				return this.intArray[i];
			}
			return -1;
		}

		public String toString() {
			return Arrays.toString(intArray);
		}
	}

Finally, in calling it; you don&#39;t want an array of `PrimitiveArray`(s), and you need to use something like the `get` and `set` methods above (since Java does not have *operator overloading*). Something like,

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Random rand = new Random();

		PrimitiveArray intArray = new PrimitiveArray(5);
		for (int i = 0; i &lt; intArray.length; i++) {
			intArray.set(i, rand.nextInt());
		}
		System.out.println(intArray);
	}

P.S. as pointed out by [@Tom](https://stackoverflow.com/users/3824919/tom) in the comments, though I initially made it so to meet with your original code; `length` should not be a `public` field and should also be accessed through a method. Like,

	public class PrimitiveArray {
		private int[] intArray;
		public int length() {
            return intArray.length;
        }

